        <chapter xml:id="week1">
            <title>Week 1 - Functions of Two Variables</title>
            <section xml:id="section12_1">
                <title>Section 12.1 - Functions of Two Variables</title>
                
                <video youtube="gvCMj5iQqk8"/>
                
                	<worksheet>
                		<exercise>
                            <p>What is the distance between the points <m>(1,3,4)</m> and <m>(9,0,4)</m>?</p>
                            <solution>
                                <p>The distance is </p>
                                <me>\sqrt{(1-9)^2+(3-0)^2+(4-4)^2}=\sqrt{64+9+0}=\sqrt{73}</me>
                            </solution>
                        </exercise>
                        <exercise>
                            <p>A bank launches a new savings account with an annual interest rate of <m>5\%</m>. Find a formula for the function of two varialbes giving the account balance <m>t</m> years after an initial investment of <m>P</m> dollars.</p>
                            <solution>
                                <p>The account balance, a function of two variables, is given by</p>
                                <me>f(t,P)=P(1.05)^t.</me>
                            </solution>
                        </exercise>
                        <exercise>
                            <p>Come up with a formula for a cylinder of radius 2 centered on the <m>x</m>-axis.</p>
                            <solution>
                                <p>The formula shouldn't involve <m>x</m> because the <m>x</m>-coordinates have no restrictions. Instead, we should think about the circle created in the <m>yz</m>-plane which has formula <m>y^2+z^2=4</m>.</p>
                            </solution>
                        </exercise>
                	</worksheet>
                                		
            </section>
            <section xml:id="section12_2_12_3">
                <title>Section 12.2/12.3 - Functions of Two Variables</title>
                    
                <video youtube="k-WFELkrz_o"/>
                    
                <worksheet>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>The contour diagram below is that of the function of monthly car payment as a function of loan size and interest rate. (Loan size is on the <m>y</m> axis, and interest rate is on the <m>x</m> axis).</p>
                        <image source="images/Math300F13Exam1G3.jpg"/>
                        <ol type="a">
                            <li>If the interest rate is <m>7.5\%</m> and you borrow <m>\$4000</m>, approximately what is your monthly payment?</li>
                            <li>If interest rates increase to <m>14\%</m> about how what size loan can you afford if the monthly payment remains the same?</li>
                        </ol>
                    </exercise>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Draw a contour diagram for <m>f(x,y)= -\sin x + y</m> using the contours <m>z=0,\pm2</m> making sure to label each contour.</p>
                        <image source="images/Math300F13Exam1G2.jpg"/>
                    </exercise>
                </worksheet>
                                            
            </section>
        </chapter>
