        <chapter xml:id="week3">
            <title>Week 3 - Dot, Cross, &amp; Derivatives</title>
            <section xml:id="section13_3">
                <title>Section 13.3 - The Dot Product</title>
                    
                <video youtube=""/>
                    
                <worksheet>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Which pairs of the vectors <m>\sqrt 3 \vec i + \vec j, 3\vec i + \sqrt 3 \vec j , \vec i - \sqrt 3 \vec j</m></p>
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>are perpendicular?</li>
                                <li>are parallel?</li>
                            </ol>
                    </exercise>

                    <exercise>
                        <p>Find the angle between the vectors</p>
                        <me>\vec v = -3\vec i + 5 \vec j + 4 \vec k \text{ and } \vec w = 2\vec j + \vec k .</me>
                    </exercise>
                    
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Find the equation of the plane containing the point <m>(2,5,4)</m> with the vector <m> \vec u = 2\vec i - 3 \vec j + \vec k</m> orthogonal to it.</p>
                    </exercise>
                </worksheet>
                                            
            </section>
            <section xml:id="section13_4">
                <title>Section 13.4 - The Cross Product</title>
                    
                <video youtube=""/>
                    
                <worksheet>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Let <m>\vec u = 3\vec i + \vec j - \vec k</m> and <m>\vec v = \vec i - 4\vec j + 2 \vec k</m>.</p>
                        <ol type="a">
                            <li>Compute <m>\vec u \times \vec v</m>.</li>
                            <li>Check that it is indeed perpendicular to <m>\vec u</m> and <m>\vec v</m>.</li>
                            <li>What can you say about <m>\vec v \times \vec u</m>?</li>
                        </ol>
                    </exercise>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Suppose that <m>\vec v \cdot \vec w = 5</m>, <m> \Vert \vec v \times \vec w \Vert = 3</m>, and the angle between <m>\vec v</m> and <m>\vec w</m> is <m>\theta</m>. Find <m>\tan \theta</m> and <m>\theta</m>.</p>
                    </exercise>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Find the area of the triangle formed by the points <m>(1,2,3)</m>, <m>(4,1,0)</m>, and <m>(3,0,7)</m>.</p>
                    </exercise>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Find the equation of the plane passing through <m>(1,2,3)</m>, <m>(4,1,0)</m>, and <m>(3,0,7)</m>.</p>
                    </exercise>
                </worksheet>
                                            
            </section>
            <section xml:id="section14_1_2">
                <title>Section 14.1/14.2 - Partial Derivatives</title>
                <video youtube=""/>
                
                <worksheet>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Compute the following partial derivatives</p>
                        <ol type="a">
                            <li><m>f_x(x,y)</m> and <m>f_y(x,y)</m> if <m>f(x,y) = 5x^2y^3+8xy^2-3x^2</m>.</li>
                            <li><m>f_x(2,3)</m> if <m>f(x,y) = (\cos x) + y</m>.</li>
                            <li><m>\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}</m> and <m>\frac{\partial V}{\partial h}</m> if <m>V=\frac 43 \pi r^2 h</m>.</li>
                            <li><m>\frac{\partial}{\partial M} \left( \frac{2\pi r^{3/2}}{\sqrt{GM}} \right)</m></li>
                        </ol>
                    </exercise>
                </worksheet>
            </section>
