        <chapter xml:id="week4">
            <title>Week 4 - Tangent Plane, Gradient, &amp; Directional Derivatives</title>
            <section xml:id="section14_3">
                <title>Section 14.3 - The Dot Product</title>
                    
                <video youtube=""/>
                    
                <worksheet>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Find the equation of the tangent plane to
                        <me> f(x,y) = \ln (x^2 + y^2) + x^2 - 3y </me>
                        at the point <m>(0,1,-3)</m>. Use it to estimate <m>f(0.1,1.1)</m>.</p>
                    </exercise>

                    <exercise>
                        <p>Find the equation of the tangent plane of the function
                        <me>f(x,y) = x^2e^{5y} </me>
                        at the point <m>(2,0)</m>. Use linear approximation to estimate <m>f(2.02,-0.01)</m>.</p>
                    </exercise>
                </worksheet>
            </section>
            <section xml:id="section14_4">
                <title>Section 14.4 - The Gradient &amp; Directional Derivatives</title>
                
                <video youtube="mfpihLrHK_s"/>
                
                <worksheet>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>Let <m>f(x,y) = \sin (x^2 + y^2)</m>.</p>
                        <ol type="a">
                            <li>Compute <m>\grad f</m>.</li>
                            <li>Compute <m>\grad f (\sqrt \pi, 0)</m></li>
                            <li>Compute the direction derivative <m>f_{\vec u} (\sqrt \pi, 0)</m> in the direction of <m>\vec u = \frac 35 \vec i - \frac 45 \vec j</m>.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </exercise>

                    <exercise>
                        <p><fn>Exercise #69 in 14.4</fn>Compute the directional derivative of <m>f(x,y) = e^x \tan (y) + 2x^2 y</m> at the point <m>(0, \pi/4)</m> in the
                        <m>\vec i - \vec j</m> direction.</p>
                    </exercise>

                    <exercise>
                        <p>Use the contour diagram of <m>f</m> shown below to answer the following questions.</p>
